Traffic Engineering Associates, Inc. (TEA) conducted a traffic study to determine the impact
of traffic generated by the addition of new sixth grade students to the MacDonald Middle
School in the City of East Lansing, Ingham County, Michigan. The school is located in the
northeast corner of Hagadorn Road and Burcham Drive. The new sixth grade students will
join seventh and eighth grade students currently at the middle school. Construction has begun
and will be completed by fall of 2014.
A level of service analysis was conducted for existing traffic at the intersection of Burcham
Drive and Hagadorn Road, as well as the two MacDonald Middle School driveways, one on
Hagadorn Road and one on Burcham Drive, during the school peak hours. All existing
turning movements operate at an acceptable level of service (LOS D or better) at the studied
intersections except for one movement. During the AM peak hour, the westbound left turning
traffic at the MacDonald Middle School driveway onto southbound Hagadorn Road operates
A trip generation estimate for the additional sixth grade traffic was determined based on
existing traffic volumes at the MacDonald Middle School and new faculty volumes. It is
projected that the proposed addition of the sixth grade students and faculty will generate 251
vehicle trips in the AM peak hour and 185 vehicle trips in the PM peak hour.
Under future conditions, the majority of the movements are expected to see little to no
increase in vehicle delay due to the additional sixth grade student and faculty traffic. The
largest increases in vehicle delay occur for westbound left turning traffic exiting the
MacDonald Middle School driveway onto southbound Hagadorn Road. During the AM
school peak hour, it is expected that the level of service will remain a LOS F with a
significant increase in delay. During the PM peak hour, it is anticipated that the level of
service will change from a LOS D to LOS F.
The study recommendations include providing a pedestrian sidewalk from Hagadorn Road to
the MacDonald Middle School for students, along the Hagadorn Road school driveway, to
separate pedestrians from vehicle traffic. At the MacDonald Middle School Driveway on
Burcham Drive, the school should consider painting the curb along the sidewalk in yellow
paint to give a visual indication that supports the existing “No Stopping, Standing, or
Parking” signs posted from the all-way stop to Burcham Drive. In addition, parents should be
encouraged to pull further into the Burcham Drive school driveway to better utilize the
designated drop-off area directly in front of the school property. When funds are available,
additional onsite storage should be considered for parent drop-off and pick-up.
It was recommended that the busses be scheduled in the afternoon school peak hour to arrive
at the middle school and be parked waiting for students to load before 3:00 PM to reduce the
pedestrian and bus conflicts when loading. In the future, a possible alternative to separate bus
and parent traffic would be to extend the driveway east of the school building as a one-way
bus exiting driveway onto Burcham Drive.
The purpose of this study is to determine the impact of traffic generated by the addition of
new sixth grade students to the MacDonald Middle School in the City of East Lansing,
Ingham County, Michigan. The school is located in the northeast corner of Hagadorn Road
and Burcham Drive. The new sixth grade students will join seventh and eighth grade students
currently at the middle school. Construction has begun and will be completed by fall of 2014.
Access to the MacDonald Middle School is provided by two (2) access driveways; one (1)
access drive on Hagadorn Road and one (1) access drive on Burcham Drive.
The scope of work contained in this report is as follows:
• Analysis of existing traffic conditions on the adjoining street system, including the
Hagadorn Road and MacDonald Middle School Driveway
Burcham Drive and MacDonald Middle School Driveway
• Projection of future fall 2014 traffic volumes to be generated by the addition of sixth
grade students and faculty to the MacDonald Middle School.
• Evaluation of the impact of future traffic at the aforementioned intersections.
• Determination of what roadway and traffic control improvements, if any, will be needed
Hagadorn Road is a four-lane north-south roadway with curb and gutter. There are sidewalks
on both sides of the roadway with a posted speed limit of 30 MPH. During school hours,
there is a flashing yellow signal posted on a 25 MPH School Zone sign to alert drivers to the
reduced speed. The roadway is under the jurisdiction of the City of East Lansing.
Burcham Drive is a three-lane east-west roadway with a center left turn lane and concrete
curb and gutter. There are bike lanes and sidewalks on both sides of the roadway. The posted
speed limit is 25 MPH. The roadway is under the jurisdiction of the City of East Lansing.
The intersection of Hagadorn Road and Burcham Drive is controlled by a traffic signal. The
north and south approaches on Hagadorn Road have four (4) lanes; one (1) left-thru lane, one
(1) thru-right turn lane and two (2) outbound lanes. The east and west approaches on
Burcham Drive have three (3) lanes; one (1) exclusive left turn lane, one (1) thru-right turn
The intersection of Hagadorn Road and the MacDonald Middle School driveway is a “T”
intersection and is controlled by a stop sign for westbound traffic at the driveway. The north
approach on Hagadorn Road has four (4) lanes with one (1) left-thru lane, one (1) thru lane,
and two (2) outbound lanes. The south approach on Hagadorn Road has one (1) thru lane, one
(1) thru-right turn lane, and two (2) outbound lanes. The east approach for the MacDonald
Middle School driveway is three (3) lanes, with one (1) exclusive left turn lane, one (1)
exclusive right turn lane and one (1) outbound lane.
The intersection of Burcham Drive and the MacDonald Middle School driveway is a “T”
intersection and is controlled by a stop sign for the southbound traffic at the driveway. The
east and west approaches on Burcham Drive have three (3) lanes with one (1) center left turn
lane, one (1) thru-right lane and one (1) outbound lane. The MacDonald Middle School
driveway has three (3) lanes with one (1) exclusive left turn lane, one (1) exclusive right turn
lane and one (1) outbound lane. This driveway is posted with a “No Left Turn 7:45-8:15 AM
and 3:00-3:30 PM” for traffic exiting school traffic at the driveway.
TEA, Inc. conducted midweek vehicle turning movement surveys during the morning and
afternoon peak periods in January, 2014, at the following locations:
• Hagadorn Road at the MacDonald Middle School Driveway
• Burcham Drive at the MacDonald Middle School Driveway
The AM and PM peak hours of existing traffic on the two (2) school driveways are 7:45-8:45
AM and 3:00-4:00 PM respectively. The existing weekday AM and PM peak hour school
traffic volumes at the above listed locations are illustrated in Figure 1.

text.b: LEVEL OF SERVICE ANALYSIS FOR EXISTING TRAFFIC

page.text: The critical intersections defined for this study were analyzed according to the methodologies
published in the most recent edition of the Highway Capacity Manual. The analysis
determines the “Level of Service” of the intersections and is based on factors such as the
number and types of lanes, signal timing, traffic volumes, pedestrian activity, etc. The level
of service (LOS) is defined by average vehicle delay in seconds created by a traffic control
device for a given traffic movement or intersection approach.
Levels of Service are expressed in a range from “A” to “F,” with “A” being the highest LOS
and “F” representing the lowest LOS. Level of service “D” is considered the minimum
acceptable LOS in an urban area.

All Level of Service computations contained in this report were based upon the Synchro 8
software package which is approved by the Michigan Department of Transportation (MDOT).

peak hours is summarized in Table 1. All existing turning movements operate at an

movement. During the AM peak hour, the westbound left turning traffic at the MacDonald

Note: Delay = Average control delay per vehicle in seconds.
The East Lansing Public Schools provided data for the proposed addition of the new sixth
grade students and faculty to the MacDonald Middle School. The school district estimated
approximately eleven (11) teachers and staff will be moved to the MacDonald Middle School
to accommodate the new sixth graders.
Information provided by school officials shows that 283 sixth grade students will be
transferred to the MacDonald Middle School. Information obtained from the East Lansing
School Transportation department indicated that approximately 68% are bussed, 12% walk to
school, and 20% are dropped off by a parent. The current busses arriving at the MacDonald
Middle School are already accommodating the sixth grade students; therefore, the school does
not expect that there will be an increase in the number of school busses. From the 20% drop
off rate estimated by the East Lansing Transportation department, it was determined that that
the trip generation for the additional traffic from the six grade students would be
approximately 57 entering and 57 exiting vehicles, for a total of 114 trips per peak hour.
A second trip generation estimate was calculated based on existing traffic volumes entering
and exiting the MacDonald Middle School driveways during the peak periods. The middle
school currently houses the seventh and eighth grade classes. For the purposes of this study,
it was assumed that the existing trips generated to the school were split evenly between each
grade, meaning that half the traffic to the site was to drop-off seventh graders and half the
traffic was to drop-off eighth graders during the AM peak hour, and the same split for pick-up
During the existing AM peak hour, 241 vehicles enter and 238 vehicles exit the school for a
total of 479 vehicles an hour. During the existing PM peak hour, 148 vehicles enter and 199
vehicles exit the school for a total of 347 vehicles an hour. During the PM peak hour, many
parents arrive early and park to wait for students; therefore, they are already on-site before the
To estimate trip generation for one grade, the existing traffic volumes were reduced by half to
represent the traffic generated by either seventh or eighth grade. With that understanding,
during the AM peak hour one grade generates approximately 120 vehicles entering and 120
vehicles exiting, for a total of 240 vehicles per grade. During the PM peak hour, one grade
generates approximately 75 vehicles entering and 99 vehicles exiting, for a total of 174
Using the above analysis for trip generation per grade, it is projected that the proposed
addition of the sixth grade students and new faculty will generate 251 vehicle trips in the AM
peak hour and 185 vehicle trips in the PM peak hour. The projected traffic to be generated by
the addition of the sixth grade students and faculty is summarized in Table 2.
Traffic distribution was based on existing traffic volume patterns on the surrounding roadway
system. During the morning school peak hour, traffic volumes were split evenly between the
two (2) school driveways. However, during the afternoon school peak hour approximately
70% of the school traffic utilized the driveway on Hagadorn Road and only 30% of the school
traffic used the driveway on Burcham Drive. These splits were used for the proposed
morning and afternoon school peak hour traffic, respectfully.

text.b: LEVEL OF SERVICE ANALYSIS FOR FUTURE TRAFFIC

page.text: The level of service analysis for future school traffic is summarized in Table 3. The majority
of the movements are expected to see little to no increase in vehicle delay due to the
additional sixth grade student and faculty traffic.
The eastbound left turn at the intersection of Hagadorn Road and Burcham Drive will drop
from LOS D to LOS E during the AM school peak hour with an increase in vehicle delay of
31.6 seconds. The westbound left turn at the intersection of Hagadorn Road and Burcham
Drive will drop from LOS C to LOS D during the AM school peak hour with an increase in
vehicle delay of 8.6 seconds. Once the transfer is complete and traffic patterns are established,
the City of East Lansing can reevaluate the traffic signal timing at this intersection.
The largest increases in vehicle delay occur for westbound left turning traffic exiting the
MacDonald Middle School driveway onto southbound Hagadorn Road. During the AM
school peak hour, it is expected that the level of service will remain a LOS F; however, the
vehicle delay will change from 50.9 seconds of delay for existing to 168.8 seconds of delay
for future, an increase of 117.9 seconds. During the PM peak hour, it is anticipated that the
level of service will change from a LOS D to LOS F and the vehicle delay will change from
an existing of 33.6 seconds of vehicle delay to 86.2 seconds of delay, an increase of 52.6
The large vehicle delays for the Hagadorn Road school driveway is caused by a combination
of the increase in parent traffic from the addition of the sixth grade students, and the lack of
available gaps in the traffic stream on Hagadorn Road which hinders the left turning vehicles
exiting the school driveway. Due to the lengthy delays, traffic queues up in the driveway
waiting for an acceptable gap to enter Hagadorn Road. This problem only occurs for a very
short period of time in the morning and afternoon during the school’s busy traffic periods. It
was also noted that the school busses exit MacDonald Middle School by using the Hagadorn
school driveway and most of them turn right, northbound, on Hagadorn Road. When a school
bus is in the right lane, it effectively blocks the view for any vehicles sitting in the left turn
lane attempting to turn onto southbound Hagadorn Road. This sight restriction also
contributes to the lengthy delays at this driveway.
A traffic signal warrant analysis was conducted for the intersection of the MacDonald Middle
School driveway and Hagadorn Road using Warrant 3 – Peak Hour, as outlined in the
Michigan Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MMUTCD), 2011 Edition. The
intersection of Hagadorn Road and the MacDonald Middle School driveway does not meet
the warrants for a traffic signal under future school traffic conditions.
All other movements are anticipated to operate at an acceptable level of service (LOS D or
better), the same as under existing conditions.
Note: Delay = Average control delay per vehicle in seconds.
Under future conditions, this intersection is expected to have one movement operate at a poor
level of service during the AM peak hour. The eastbound left turn movement drops from the
existing conditions LOS D to the future conditions of LOS E. Overall the intersection is
expected to operate at an acceptable level of service during the AM peak hour. Once the sixth
grade students are transferred, and traffic patterns are established, the City of East Lansing
can reevaluate the traffic signal timing at this intersection.
Hagadorn Road and MacDonald Middle School Driveway
The westbound left turning traffic from the MacDonald Middle School driveway onto
southbound Hagadorn Road currently operates with lengthy vehicle delays during the
morning school peak hour. With the addition of the sixth grade students and faculty, the
vehicle delay for this left turn movement will increase and will continue to operate at level of
service “F” during the school morning and afternoon peak hours. A traffic signal warrant
analysis was conducted at this driveway to determine if a traffic signal is warranted for either
the AM or PM school peak times to mitigate vehicle delays. The results show that a traffic
signal is not warranted at this location.
High vehicle delays at the Hagadorn Road driveway are occurring when parents, students and
busses are arriving and exiting the school property in a short time frame, as well as the steady
traffic volumes on Hagadorn Road. In addition, when a school bus is in the right lane it
effectively blocks the view for any vehicles sitting in the left turn lane attempting to turn onto
southbound Hagadorn Road. This sight restriction also contributes to the lengthy delays at
An option to mitigate this would be to restrict left turns onto Hagadorn Road
during peak periods; however, this restriction is already posted at the driveway on Burcham
Road and having both driveways posted with restricted left turns would not allow motorists
from either driveway to travel east on Burcham Drive.
Another option would be to separate the parents and busses by requiring the parents to use the
Burcham Drive driveway and restrict the Hagadorn Road driveway to staff and busses only.
This would significantly reduce left turn delays at the Hagadorn Road driveway, and by
removing the parents, would allow free access for the busses. However, this option would
most likely overload the Burcham Drive driveway due to the heavy parent-drop off volumes.
Under the current driveway and parking lot layout, access to both driveways contributes to the
As a possible future alternative, the school could extend the driveway east of the school
building to Burcham Drive for a bus exit only driveway. The one-way bus pattern would
arrive from Hagadorn Road, drop off or load students, then continue along the east side of the
middle school building and exit onto Burcham Drive. This would allow the busses to utilize
the signal at Hagadorn Road and Burcham Drive to travel north, south, or west. Parents
would then have access to Hagadorn Road without the delays or sight distance restrictions
from busses utilizing the same driveway. The new access point onto Burcham Drive would
need to be posted as a one-way exit with “Do Not Enter” signs for traffic on Burcham Drive.
Burcham Drive and MacDonald Middle School Driveway
The analysis shows this intersection operates well under both existing and future conditions.
There are no recommended geometric or traffic control improvements at this location. It
should be noted that during the data collection process, it was observed that motorists are
disregarding the left turn restriction onto Burcham Drive and turning left from the school
driveway during peak periods in order to access eastbound destinations.
From conversations with school officials, and officials from the City of East Lansing, no one
knew the history of the left turn restriction that is posted at the Burcham Road driveway.
From field observation during data collection, motorists are currently driving this intersection
as though the left turn restriction were not there. If the left turn restriction were removed,
those parents wanting to go east on Burcham Drive will not be forced to use the Hagadorn
Road driveway and it might relieve some of the left turning traffic volumes onto southbound
A site visit was conducted to determine if there are any site circulation issues at the
MacDonald Middle School. The school driveway on Burcham Drive is currently posted “No
Left Turn” from 7:45-8:15 AM and 3:00-3:30 PM. A review of the site, as well as data
collection counts, reveal that some parents are ignoring the left turn restriction signs and
completing a left turn during the restricted time intervals. The analysis shows that there is
very little delay on the driveway from the few left turning vehicles.
The morning onsite traffic flow appears to work smoothly. Parents are utilizing both the cul-
de-sac turn around at the Burcham Drive driveway in front of the middle school, as well as
the parking lot as a drop off area. The marked pedestrian crosswalk on the Burcham Drive
driveway in front of the school building is protected by an all-way stop control and provides
students with a safe crossing from the parking lot to the school building. In the morning,
busses arrive via the Hagadorn Road driveway and drop students off on the north side of the
school building at the sidewalk, which separates the busses from parent drop-off operations.
Ample sidewalks are provided to accommodate all pedestrian movements adjacent to the
It was noted that students walking to school walk along the Hagadorn Road driveway as there
is no sidewalk from Hagadorn Road to the school building to accommodate them. It was
observed that there are trails through the snow next to the driveway where students have made
their own pedestrian walkway adjacent to the driveway to get between the school building and
Hagadorn Road. Due to the heavy vehicle traffic utilizing this driveway, it would be
recommended to provide a paved pedestrian sidewalk from Hagadorn Road to the school
During the afternoon school peak hour, when school lets out, the onsite traffic operation is
more congested. Parents begin to arrive before the 3:04 PM dismissal time and line up along
the Burcham Drive school driveway. During the afternoon school peak hour when the onsite
observation was conducted, four (4) vehicles were parked in the pick-up area north of the all-
way stop directly in front of the school. The remaining waiting vehicles were parked in the
inbound travel lane of the Burcham Drive driveway starting from the all-way stop sign and
extending to the south to Burcham Drive. It was observed that a maximum of twelve (12)
vehicles could stack from the multi-way stop sign in the driveway to Burcham Drive. It was
also observed that there were two (2) vehicles parked in the eastbound center left turn lane on
Burcham Drive, waiting to complete their left turn into the school driveway; however, the
inbound traffic lane in the school driveway was full and blocked by waiting vehicles. It was
noted that two (2) vehicles ignored the parked vehicles and entered the school driveway and
traveled northbound in the southbound exiting lane to the all-way stop sign, and then turned
The school currently has the driveway on Burcham Drive posted as “No Stopping, Standing,
or Parking” between the all-way stop and Burcham Drive. At two (2) different site visits, it
was observed that parents are disregarding the signs and parking along the driveway on the
inbound lane. As the current signs are not working, an option would be to paint the curb
along the sidewalk in yellow paint which would help to give a visual indication that parking is
not allowed and try to discourage parents from parking there. Another option would be to
contact the East Lansing Police Department to discuss the possibility of installing different
signing that would be enforceable by the police department.
It was observed that there was available room for more vehicles to park in the pick-up area
directly in front of the school. With approximately 150 feet of storage, and an approximate
20 foot space per vehicle, it is estimated that seven (7) to eight (8) vehicles could be parked in
front of the school. Encouraging parents to pull further onto the site would allow for
additional storage in this designated area. When funds are available, it would be advantageous
to consider additional onsite storage for parents waiting to pick up their student.
It was also noted that four (4) vehicles were parked in the public roadway along the curb on
the north side of Burcham Drive, adjacent to the school property, waiting for students. The
vehicles were parked partially in the marked bike lane and partially in the westbound travel
lane. As these vehicles are illegally parked, the problem can be remedied with enforcement
by the East Lansing Police Department.
Many parents entered the school property using the Hagadorn Road driveway and parked in
the parking lot on the west side of the school building to wait for their student. During the
busiest time when parents were arriving to pick up their child, it was observed that
approximately one third (1/3) of the total parking spaces were available but not utilized.
When school is dismissed, the parking lot becomes congested with students walking between
vehicles and in the drive isles looking for parents. Contributing to the congestion are vehicles
entering and exiting the parking lot, as well as parents stopping in the drive isles waiting for
their student, which blocks parked vehicles from exiting. Parents should be encouraged to
park in parking spaces, rather than stopping in the drive isles to wait for students. This would
reduce congestion onsite and would reduce conflicts between vehicles and pedestrians.
Busses began to arrive just after 3:00 PM. They enter the school property using the Hagadorn
Road driveway and were intermixed with parent traffic also using this driveway. Parents
waiting to pick up their student created a circle around the parking lot that backed up to the
Hagadorn Road driveway, creating a back up down the driveway, which caused the busses to
be delayed getting to the student loading area. When busses arrived at the student loading
area north of the middle school building, students were already waiting and walking in the bus
This creates a potential safety concern for pedestrian and bus conflicts.
mitigate this, it would be recommended that the busses arrive with ample time to be parked
and waiting before students are dismissed. It was observed that parent traffic became the
heaviest around 3:00 PM; therefore, it would be advised that busses arrive and be parked in
the student loading area prior to 3:00 PM to avoid the delays created by having to mix with
the parent traffic queued in the Hagadorn Road driveway.

Sneathen briefly discussed the personnel and type of work handled by the Department of Public Works. The type of work performed ranges from street maintenance, infrastructure maintenance, project design, rubbish and yard waste collection and park mai...
The Department of Public Works plays a vital role in maintaining current systems within the City and continues to make improvements while providing efficient service.

Sneathen discussed the City's snow removal policy and how property owners play a pivotal role in maintaining sidewalks adjacent to their property. City crews currently maintain the State Trunklines within the City Limits, as well as all local and maj...
Hittner asked approximately how long it takes for crews to clear the City streets of snow.

Sneathen stated that City streets can be cleared in approximately 10 hours using 4-5 trucks. If a substantial amount of snow has fallen and continues to fall, it can take days as major streets require multiple passes within a 24 hour time frame.
Hollstein inquired about the removal of snow from City parking lots.

Sneathen stated snow removal downtown is handled immediately by crews, which includes parking garages and small parking lots. Sneathen added that a report will be presented to City Council by P.A.C.E. and the Building Department on snow...

Sneathen announced that this will be his last Transportation Commission meeting as he has accepted a new position. He introduced Robert Scheuerman, current Engineering Administrator who will sit in on upcoming meetings.
